abstract: Real estate websites are supplying home buyers with hyper-specific community data, including racial makeup, percent of married households and education level.

lead_paragraph: When Eugenia Spektor and her husband decided it was time to leave Long Island City for the suburbs, they knew the kind of community they wanted to live in, but weren’t sure they could find it. Their list of wants was straightforward: good public schools for their two children, a train commute of no more than an hour, walking distance to town, an easygoing atmosphere. The characteristics they hoped to avoid were harder to divine: success-crazed moms, high-pressure schools and, since they work full time, a predominance of stay-at-home parents.

abstract: America’s most vulnerable comedian jokes about O.C.D., psych wards, even suicide. Somehow it’s all very funny.
snippet: America’s most vulnerable comedian jokes about O.C.D., psych wards, even suicide. Somehow it’s all very funny.
lead_paragraph: Maria Bamford has a mantra of sorts, and here it is: Do the work. Three words, three syllables. An easy, orderly thing. She tells it to herself when she wakes up in the morning, whether it’s at her bungalow in a middle-class neighborhood on the outskirts of Los Angeles or at a Holiday Inn in Boston or a Marriott in Bloomington, or any of the other highway-side hotels she hits for one night before moving on. Do the work. It’s a stay against paralysis, against the descent of dread. It’s less dramatic than “seize the day!” more affirming than “stop overthinking everything!” It is functional, and that’s what she’s trying to be. Do the work. She repeats it on airplanes, in taxis, on the long walks she takes to calm her nerves before a show. Sometimes she amends it to: Just do the work, the “just” a reminder that she’s not, after all, performing surgery on babies. There’s another, more refined version, too. Do your bits, she’ll tell herself, resigned to the idea that this may always be a struggle. Just do your bits.

headline_main: The Weird, Scary and Ingenious Brain of Maria Bamford

abstract: To keep shots below the wind and out of pothole bunkers, golfers often prefer 2-irons instead of drivers off the tee at a links course like Royal Liverpool, home of this year’s British Open.
snippet: To keep shots below the wind and out of pothole bunkers, golfers often prefer 2-irons instead of drivers off the tee at a links course like Royal Liverpool, home of this year’s British Open.
lead_paragraph: HOYLAKE, England — Players take great care setting the table for the British Open, a formal — and for many, foreign — event. For this one week, many will take out and polish off a club that, like a salad fork, is reserved for special occasions. It is the 2-iron, the nearest thing the golfers have in their bag to a repellent for the British links courses’ biggest pest, the pothole bunker.

abstract: Tiger Woods has had highs and lows through the years at the British Open, but he’s always been in the spotlight.
snippet: Tiger Woods has had highs and lows through the years at the British Open, but he’s always been in the spotlight.
lead_paragraph: HOYLAKE, England — Win or more often lose, Tiger Woods has never passed unnoticed at a British Open, from his debut as a teenage amateur in 1995 to his final-day fade from contention in 2013.

abstract: Glenn Burke’s family has been invited to Tuesday’s All-Star Game in Minneapolis — recognition of his early role in a movement gaining traction across the sports landscape.
snippet: Glenn Burke’s family has been invited to Tuesday’s All-Star Game in Minneapolis — recognition of his early role in a movement gaining traction across the sports landscape.
lead_paragraph: EMERYVILLE, Calif. — Glenn Burke was 27 when he walked out on Major League Baseball, his promising career as an outfielder undone mostly by the burden of being a semicloseted gay man. It was 1980, and it was more important, Burke later explained, to be himself than to be a professional baseball player.

abstract: Flush with money and momentum, Republicans are confident that they can at least maintain the gains they made in governors' races four years ago.
snippet: Flush with money and momentum, Republicans are confident that they can at least maintain the gains they made in governors' races four years ago.
lead_paragraph: NASHVILLE — Republican candidates for governor around the country have built an unexpectedly strong position for election this fall, helped by an improving economy, disaffection with President Obama and a national fund-raising machine that is leagues ahead of the opposition.

abstract: A New York City man fell in love with Citroëns when he was 17 and now owns three of them, including the sporty SM model that’s his daily driver.
snippet: A New York City man fell in love with Citroëns when he was 17 and now owns three of them, including the sporty SM model that’s his daily driver.
lead_paragraph: One Thursday last fall, Brian Brandt got a phone call from “The Americans,” the FX Networks’ period drama about Cold War-era Soviet spies living in a Washington suburb. An anxious member of the production staff explained that the show, filmed in a Brooklyn studio and at locations around Long Island, needed a car repaired — and back on the set the following Tuesday.

abstract: Masahiro Tanaka, the Yankees’ ace, will be out at least six weeks. If his elbow fails to respond to the prescribed rehabilitation program, it could eventually require reconstructive Tommy John surgery.
snippet: Masahiro Tanaka, the Yankees’ ace, will be out at least six weeks. If his elbow fails to respond to the prescribed rehabilitation program, it could eventually require reconstructive Tommy John surgery.
lead_paragraph: CLEVELAND — The Yankees put their ace, Masahiro Tanaka, on a plane to Seattle on Thursday to have his ailing right elbow examined, and then there was nothing else they could do but hope.
